\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, substitute 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{2}+\left(tx+1\right)^{2}-1=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(1+t^{2}\right)x^{2}+2tx=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
One solution is 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, which we already knew since 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 passes through 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The other is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\frac{-2t}{1+t^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{-2t}{1+t^{2}}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y=\frac{-2t^{2}}{1+t^{2}}+1=\frac{1-t^{2}}{1+t^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Arbitrarily dropping the sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, the rational parametrization is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{{C}}:\left[\frac{2t}{1+t^{2}},\frac{1-t^{2}}{1+t^{2}}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
These rational coordinates are the lengths of the sides of a right triangle
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{{C}}$
\end_inset

's radius as its hypoteneuse.
 So
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{2t}{1+t^{2}}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{1-t^{2}}{1+t^{2}}\right)^{2}=1\label{eq:5}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(2t\right)^{2}+\left(1-t^{2}\right)^{2}=\left(1+t^{2}\right)^{2}\label{eq:3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The terms of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3"

\end_inset

 can be used as a generator of Pythagorean triples.
 The RHS is a perfect square and could alternatively be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(a^{2}+t^{2}\right)^{2}=a^{4}+2a^{2}t^{2}+t^{4}=(2at)^{2}+(a^{2}-t^{2})^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(2at)^{2}+(a^{2}-t^{2})^{2}=\left(a^{2}+t^{2}\right)^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{2at}{a^{2}+t^{2}}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{a^{2}-t^{2}}{a^{2}+t^{2}}\right)^{2}=1\label{eq:4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Equating terms in the LHS of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:4"

\end_inset

 with those of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:5"

\end_inset

 yields the more general parametrization:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{{C}}:\left[\frac{2at}{a^{2}+t^{2}},\frac{a^{2}-t^{2}}{a^{2}+t^{2}}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

